[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] In addition, **Narrative visualization** is a method that uses visual elements such as charts, graphs, maps and the like to convey data or information.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] This approach blends data analysis, storytelling, and visualization to present information through structured narrative flows- *using visuals not just to present statistics, but to tell a story through data*.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] Its goal is to help people identify trends, patterns, and relationships in data through a compelling story-driven visual experience.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] Emerging technologies like virtual, augmented and mixed reality have the potential to make information visualization more immersive, intuitive, interactive and easily manipulable and thus enhance the user's visual perception and cognition.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] Effective data visualization is well-sourced, appropriately contextualized, and presented in a simple, uncluttered manner.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] The underlying data is accurate and up-to-date to ensure insights are reliable.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] Graphical items are well-chosen and aesthetically appealing, with shapes, colors and other visual elements used deliberately in a meaningful and non-distracting manner.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] The visuals are accompanied by supporting texts.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] Verbal and graphical components complement each other to ensure clear, quick and memorable understanding.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] Effective information visualization is aware of the needs and expertise level of the target audience.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] Data scientists, analysts and data mining specialists use data visualization to check data quality, find errors, unusual gaps, missing values, clean data, explore the structures and features of data, and assess outputs of data-driven models.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] Data and information visualization can be part of *data storytelling*, where they are paired with a narrative structure, to contextualize the analyzed data and communicate insights gained from analyzing it to convince the audience into making a decision or taking action.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] Data and information visualization is interdisciplinary, it incorporates principles found in descriptive statistics, visual communication, graphic design, cognitive science and, interactive computer graphics and human-computer interaction.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] Since effective visualization requires design skills, statistical skills and computing skills, it is both an art and a science.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] Visual analytics combines statistical data analysis, data and information visualization, and human analytical reasoning through interactive visual interfaces to help users reach conclusions, gain actionable insights and make informed decisions which are otherwise difficult for computers to do.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] Research into how people read and misread types of visualizations helps to determine what types and features of visualizations are most understandable and effective.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] Unintentionally poor or intentionally misleading and deceptive visualizations can function as powerful tools which disseminate misinformation, manipulate public perception and divert public opinion.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] Thus data visualization literacy has become an important component of data and information literacy in the information age akin to the roles played by textual, mathematical and visual literacy in the past.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] The field of data and information visualization has emerged "from research in human–computer interaction, computer science, graphics, visual design, psychology, photography and business methods.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] It is increasingly applied as a critical component in scientific research, digital libraries, data mining, financial data analysis, market studies, manufacturing production control, and drug discovery".
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] Data and information visualization presumes that "visual representations and interaction techniques take advantage of the human eye's broad bandwidth pathway into the mind to allow users to see, explore, and understand large amounts of information at once.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] Data analysis is an indispensable part of all applied research and problem solving in industry.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] Among these approaches, information visualization, or visual data analysis, is the most reliant on the cognitive skills of human analysts, and allows the discovery of unstructured actionable insights that are limited only by human imagination and creativity.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] The analyst does not have to learn any sophisticated methods to be able to interpret the visualizations of the data.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] Information visualization is also a hypothesis generation scheme, which can be, and is typically followed by more analytical or formal analysis, such as statistical hypothesis testing.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] To communicate information clearly and efficiently, data visualization uses statistical graphics, plots, information graphics and other tools.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] Numerical data may be encoded using dots, lines, or bars, to visually communicate a quantitative message.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] Effective visualization helps users analyze and reason about data and evidence.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] It makes complex data more accessible, understandable, and usable, but can also be reductive.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] Users may have particular analytical tasks, such as making comparisons or understanding causality, and the design principle of the graphic (i.e., showing comparisons or showing causality) follows the task.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] Tables are generally used where users will look up a specific measurement, while charts of various types are used to show patterns or relationships in the data for one or more variables.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] Data visualization refers to the techniques used to communicate data or information by encoding it as visual objects (e.g., points, lines, or bars) contained in graphics.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] The goal is to communicate information clearly and efficiently to users.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] It is one of the steps in data analysis or data science.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] According to Vitaly Friedman (2008) the "main goal of data visualization is to communicate information clearly and effectively through graphical means.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] It doesn't mean that data visualization needs to look boring to be functional or extremely sophisticated to look beautiful.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] To convey ideas effectively, both aesthetic form and functionality need to go hand in hand, providing insights into a rather sparse and complex data set by communicating its key aspects in a more intuitive way.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] Yet designers often fail to achieve a balance between form and function, creating gorgeous data visualizations which fail to serve their main purpose — to communicate information".
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] Wattenberg suggested that an ideal visualization should not only communicate clearly, but stimulate viewer engagement and attention.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] Data visualization is closely related to information graphics, information visualization, scientific visualization, exploratory data analysis and statistical graphics.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] In the new millennium, data visualization has become an active area of research, teaching and development.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] (2002), it has united scientific and information visualization.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] In the commercial environment data visualization is often referred to as dashboards.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] Infographics are another very common form of data visualization.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] Edward Tufte has explained that users of information displays are executing particular *analytical tasks* such as making comparisons.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] The *design principle* of the information graphic should support the analytical task.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] As William Cleveland and Robert McGill show, different graphical elements accomplish this more or less effectively.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] For example, dot plots and bar charts outperform pie charts.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] In his 1983 book *The Visual Display of Quantitative Information*, Edward Tufte defines 'graphical displays' and principles for effective graphical display in the following passage: "Excellence in statistical graphics consists of complex ideas communicated with clarity, precision, and efficiency.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] For example, the Minard diagram shows the losses suffered by Napoleon's army in the 1812–1813 period.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] Six variables are plotted: the size of the army, its location on a two-dimensional surface (x and y), time, the direction of movement, and temperature.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] The line width illustrates a comparison (size of the army at points in time), while the temperature axis suggests a cause of the change in army size.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] This multivariate display on a two-dimensional surface tells a story that can be grasped immediately while identifying the source data to build credibility.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] Not applying these principles may result in misleading graphs, distorting the message, or supporting an erroneous conclusion.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] According to Tufte, chartjunk refers to the extraneous interior decoration of the graphic that does not enhance the message or gratuitous three-dimensional or perspective effects.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] Needlessly separating the explanatory key from the image itself, requiring the eye to travel back and forth from the image to the key, is a form of "administrative debris." The ratio of "data to ink" should be maximized, erasing non-data ink where feasible.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] The Congressional Budget Office summarized several best practices for graphical displays in a June 2014 presentation.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] These included: a) Knowing your audience; b) Designing graphics that can stand alone outside the report's context; and c) Designing graphics that communicate the key messages in the report.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] For greatest efficiency and simplicity of design and user experience, this readability is enhanced through the use of bijective mapping in that design of the image elements - where the mapping of representational element to data variable is unique.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] Kosara (2007) also identifies the need for a visualisation to be "recognisable as a visualisation and not appear to be something else".
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] He also states that recognisability and readability may not always be required in all types of visualisation e.g.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] "informative art" (which would still meet all three above criteria but might not look like a visualisation) or "artistic visualisation" (which similarly is still based on non-visual data to create an image, but may not be readable or recognisable).
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] Ranking: Categorical subdivisions are ranked in ascending or descending order, such as a ranking of sales performance (the *measure*) by sales persons (the *category*, with each sales person a *categorical subdivision*) during a single period.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] A bar chart may be used to show the comparison across the sales persons.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] Part-to-whole: Categorical subdivisions are measured as a ratio to the whole (i.e., a percentage out of 100%).
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] A pie chart or bar chart can show the comparison of ratios, such as the market share represented by competitors in a market.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] Deviation: Categorical subdivisions are compared against a reference, such as a comparison of actual vs. budget expenses for several departments of a business for a given time period.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] A bar chart can show comparison of the actual versus the reference amount.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] Frequency distribution: Shows the number of observations of a particular variable for given interval, such as the number of years in which the stock market return is between intervals such as 0–10%, 11–20%, etc.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] A histogram, a type of bar chart, may be used for this analysis.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] A boxplot helps visualize key statistics about the distribution, such as median, quartiles, outliers, etc.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] Correlation: Comparison between observations represented by two variables (X,Y) to determine if they tend to move in the same or opposite directions.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] For example, plotting unemployment (X) and inflation (Y) for a sample of months.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] A scatter plot is typically used for this message.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] Nominal comparison: Comparing categorical subdivisions in no particular order, such as the sales volume by product code.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] A bar chart may be used for this comparison.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] Geographic or geospatial: Comparison of a variable across a map or layout, such as the unemployment rate by state or the number of persons on the various floors of a building.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] Analysts reviewing a set of data may consider whether some or all of the messages and graphic types above are applicable to their task and audience.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] The process of trial and error to identify meaningful relationships and messages in the data is part of exploratory data analysis.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] A human can distinguish differences in line length, shape, orientation, distances, and color (hue) readily without significant processing effort; these are referred to as "pre-attentive attributes".
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] For example, it may require significant time and effort ("attentive processing") to identify the number of times the digit "5" appears in a series of numbers; but if that digit is different in size, orientation, or color, instances of the digit can be noted quickly through pre-attentive processing.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] Compelling graphics take advantage of pre-attentive processing and attributes and the relative strength of these attributes.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] For example, since humans can more easily process differences in line length than surface area, it may be more effective to use a bar chart (which takes advantage of line length to show comparison) rather than pie charts (which use surface area to show comparison).
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] Almost all data visualizations are created for human consumption.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] Knowledge of human perception and cognition is necessary when designing intuitive visualizations.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] Cognition refers to processes in human beings like perception, attention, learning, memory, thought, concept formation, reading, and problem solving.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] Human visual processing is efficient in detecting changes and making comparisons between quantities, sizes, shapes and variations in lightness.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] When properties of symbolic data are mapped to visual properties, humans can browse through large amounts of data efficiently.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] It is estimated that 2/3 of the brain's neurons can be involved in visual processing.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] Proper visualization provides a different approach to show potential connections, relationships, etc. which are not as obvious in non-visualized quantitative data.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] Visualization can become a means of data exploration.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] Studies have shown individuals used on average 19% less cognitive resources, and 4.5% better able to recall details when comparing data visualization with text.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] There is no comprehensive history of data visualization.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] There are no accounts that span the entire development of visual thinking and visual representation of data, and which collate the contributions of disparate disciplines.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] Michael Friendly and Daniel Denis of York University are engaged in a project that attempts to provide a comprehensive history of visualization.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] Data visualization is not a modern development.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] Since prehistory, stellar data, or information such as location of stars were visualized on the walls of caves (such as those found in Lascaux Cave in Southern France) since the Pleistocene era.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] Physical artefacts such as Mesopotamian clay tokens (5500 BC), Inca quipus (2600 BC) and Marshall Islands stick charts (n.d.) can also be considered as visualizing quantitative information.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] The first documented data visualization can be tracked back to 1160 B.C. with the Turin Papyrus Map which accurately illustrates the distribution of geological resources and provides information about quarrying of those resources.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] Such maps can be categorized as thematic cartography, which is a type of data visualization that presents and communicates specific data and information through a geographical illustration designed to show a particular theme connected with a specific geographic area.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] Earliest documented forms of data visualization were various thematic maps from different cultures and ideograms and hieroglyphs that provided and allowed interpretation of information illustrated.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] For example, Linear B tablets of Mycenae provided a visualization of information regarding Late Bronze Age era trades in the Mediterranean.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] The idea of coordinates was used by ancient Egyptian surveyors in laying out towns, earthly and heavenly positions were located by something akin to latitude and longitude at least by 200 BC, and the map projection of a spherical Earth into latitude and longitude by Claudius Ptolemy [c.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] 165] in Alexandria would serve as reference standards until the 14th century.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] The invention of paper and parchment allowed further development of visualizations.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] One graph from the 10th or possibly 11th century is an illustration of planetary movements, used in an appendix of a textbook in monastery schools.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] The graph apparently was meant to represent a plot of the inclinations of the planetary orbits as a function of the time.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] For this purpose, the zone of the zodiac was represented on a plane with a horizontal line divided into thirty parts as the time or longitudinal axis.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] The vertical axis designates the width of the zodiac.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] The horizontal scale appears to have been chosen for each planet individually for the periods cannot be reconciled.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] The accompanying text refers only to the amplitudes.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] The curves are apparently not related in time.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] By the 16th century, techniques and instruments for precise observation and measurement of physical quantities, and geographic and celestial position were well-developed (for example, a "wall quadrant" constructed by Tycho Brahe [1546–1601], covering an entire wall in his observatory).
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] Particularly important were the development of triangulation and other methods to determine mapping locations accurately.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] Very early, the measure of time led scholars to develop innovative way of visualizing the data (e.g.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] Lorenz Codomann in 1596, Johannes Temporarius in 1596).
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] Mathematicians René Descartes and Pierre de Fermat developed analytic geometry and two-dimensional coordinate system which heavily influenced the practical methods of displaying and calculating values.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] Fermat and Blaise Pascal's work on statistics and probability theory laid the groundwork for what we now conceptualize as data.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] These developments helped William Playfair, who saw potential for graphical communication of quantitative data, to generate and develop graphical methods of statistics.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] In 1786, Playfair published the first presentation graphics.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] In the second half of the 20th century, Jacques Bertin used quantitative graphs to represent information "intuitively, clearly, accurately, and efficiently".
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] John Tukey and Edward Tufte pushed the bounds of data visualization; Tukey with his new statistical approach of exploratory data analysis and Tufte with his book "The Visual Display of Quantitative Information" paved the way for refining data visualization techniques for more than statisticians.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] With the progression of technology came the progression of data visualization; starting with hand-drawn visualizations and evolving into more technical applications – including interactive designs leading to software visualization.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] The modern study of visualization started with computer graphics, which "has from its beginning been used to study scientific problems.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] However, in its early days the lack of graphics power often limited its usefulness.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] The recent emphasis on visualization started in 1987 with the special issue of Computer Graphics on Visualization in *Scientific Computing*.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] Since then there have been several conferences and workshops, co-sponsored by the IEEE Computer Society and ACM SIGGRAPH".
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] They have been devoted to the general topics of data visualization, information visualization and scientific visualization, and more specific areas such as volume visualization.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] Programs like SAS, SOFA, R, Minitab, Cornerstone and more allow for data visualization in the field of statistics.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] Other data visualization applications, more focused and unique to individuals, programming languages such as D3, Python (through matplotlib, seaborn) and JavaScript and Java(through JavaFX) help to make the visualization of quantitative data a possibility.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] Private schools have also developed programs to meet the demand for learning data visualization and associated programming libraries, including free programs like The Data Incubator or paid programs like General Assembly.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] Beginning with the symposium "Data to Discovery" in 2013, ArtCenter College of Design, Caltech and JPL in Pasadena have run an annual program on interactive data visualization.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] The program asks: How can interactive data visualization help scientists and engineers explore their data more effectively?
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] How can computing, design, and design thinking help maximize research results?
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] What methodologies are most effective for leveraging knowledge from these fields?
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] In recent years, with the increasing popularity of games, data and information visualization has been gradually applied in the gaming industry through the use of analytical tools to assess player statistics and game performance, which are visualized in the form of health points, maps, and diagrams.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] The data is then collected and stored by developers.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] The implementation of these tools in gaming assists developers in improving user experience and in the development and updating of newer games.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] Data visualization involves specific terminology, some of which is derived from statistics.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] The distinction between quantitative and categorical variables is important because the two types require different methods of visualization.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] Two primary types of information displays are tables and graphs.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] Eppler and Lengler have developed the "Periodic Table of Visualization Methods," an interactive chart displaying various data visualization methods.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] It includes six types of data visualization methods: data, information, concept, strategy, metaphor and compound.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] Interactive data visualization has been a pursuit of statisticians since the late 1960s.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] Examples of the developments can be found on the American Statistical Association video lending library.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] There are different approaches on the scope of data visualization.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] One common focus is on information presentation, such as Friedman (2008).
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] Friendly (2008) presumes two main parts of data visualization: statistical graphics, and thematic cartography.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] All these subjects are closely related to graphic design and information representation.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] Within The Harvard Business Review, Scott Berinato developed a framework to approach data visualisation.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] To start thinking visually, users must consider two questions; 1) What you have and 2) what you're doing.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] The first step is identifying what data you want visualised.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] It is data-driven like profit over the past ten years or a conceptual idea like how a specific organisation is structured.
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] Once this question is answered one can then focus on whether they are trying to communicate information (declarative visualisation) or trying to figure something out (exploratory visualisation).
[src:altair-viz/data-visualization-p01] Scott Berinato combines these questions to give four types of visual communication that each have their own goals.
[src:altair-viz/declarative-programming] In computer science, **declarative programming** is a programming paradigm that expresses the logic of a computation without fully describing its control flow.
[src:altair-viz/declarative-programming] This is in contrast with imperative programming, which implements algorithms in explicit steps.
[src:altair-viz/declarative-programming] Declarative programming may consider programs as theories of a formal logic, and computations as deductions in that logical theory.
[src:altair-viz/declarative-programming] Declarative programming at times simplifies the writing of parallel programs.
[src:altair-viz/declarative-programming] Common declarative language paradigms include logic programming (e.g., Prolog, Datalog, answer set programming), and algebraic modeling systems.
[src:altair-viz/declarative-programming] Declarative programming is often defined as any style of programming that is not imperative.
[src:altair-viz/declarative-programming] A number of other common definitions attempt to define it by simply contrasting it with imperative programming.
[src:altair-viz/declarative-programming] These definitions overlap substantially.
[src:altair-viz/declarative-programming] Declarative programming is a non-imperative style of programming in which programs describe their desired results without explicitly listing commands or steps that must be performed.
[src:altair-viz/declarative-programming] Logic programming languages are characterized by a mostly declarative programming style.
[src:altair-viz/declarative-programming] In logic programming, programs consist of sentences expressed in logical form, and computation uses those sentences to solve problems, which are also expressed in logical form.
[src:altair-viz/declarative-programming] In a pure functional language, such as Haskell, all functions are without side effects, and state changes are only represented as functions that transform the state, which is explicitly represented as a first-class object in the program.
[src:altair-viz/declarative-programming] Although pure functional languages are non-imperative, they often provide a facility for describing the effect of a function as a series of steps.
[src:altair-viz/declarative-programming] Other functional languages, such as Lisp, OCaml and Erlang, support a mixture of procedural and functional programming.
[src:altair-viz/declarative-programming] Some logic programming languages, such as Prolog, and database query languages, such as SQL, while declarative in principle, also support a procedural style of programming.
[src:altair-viz/declarative-programming] Declarative programming is an umbrella term that includes a number of better-known programming paradigms.
[src:altair-viz/declarative-programming] Constraint programming states relations between variables in the form of constraints that specify the properties of the target solution.
[src:altair-viz/declarative-programming] The set of constraints is solved by giving a value to each variable so that the solution is consistent with the maximum number of constraints.
[src:altair-viz/declarative-programming] Constraint programming often complements other paradigms: functional, logical, or even imperative programming.
[src:altair-viz/declarative-programming] Makefiles, for example, specify dependencies in a declarative fashion, but include an imperative list of actions to take as well.
[src:altair-viz/declarative-programming] Similarly, yacc specifies a context free grammar declaratively, but includes code snippets from a host language, which is usually imperative (such as C).
[src:altair-viz/declarative-programming] Logic programming languages, such as Prolog, Datalog and answer set programming, compute by proving that a goal is a logical consequence of the program, or by showing that the goal is true in a model defined by the program.
[src:altair-viz/declarative-programming] Prolog computes by reducing goals to subgoals, top-down using backward reasoning, whereas most Datalog systems compute bottom-up using forward reasoning.
[src:altair-viz/declarative-programming] Answer set programs typically use SAT solvers to generate a model of the program.
[src:altair-viz/declarative-programming] Models, or mathematical representations, of physical systems may be implemented in computer code that is declarative.
[src:altair-viz/declarative-programming] The code contains a number of equations, not imperative assignments, that describe ("declare") the behavioral relationships.
[src:altair-viz/declarative-programming] When a model is expressed in this formalism, a computer is able to perform algebraic manipulations to best formulate the solution algorithm.
[src:altair-viz/declarative-programming] The mathematical causality is typically imposed at the boundaries of the physical system, while the behavioral description of the system itself is declarative or acausal.
[src:altair-viz/declarative-programming] Declarative modeling languages and environments include Analytica, Modelica and Simile.
[src:altair-viz/declarative-programming] Prolog (1972) stands for "PROgramming in LOGic." It was developed for natural language question answering, using SL resolution both to deduce answers to queries and to parse and generate natural language sentences.
[src:altair-viz/declarative-programming] The building blocks of a Prolog program are *facts* and *rules*.
[src:altair-viz/declarative-programming] Given this program, the query `eat(tom,jerry)` succeeds, while `eat(jerry,tom)` fails.
[src:altair-viz/declarative-programming] Moreover, the query `eat(X,jerry)` succeeds with the answer substitution `X=tom`.
[src:altair-viz/declarative-programming] Prolog executes programs top-down, using SLD resolution to reason backwards, reducing goals to subgoals.
[src:altair-viz/declarative-programming] In this example, it uses the last rule of the program to reduce the goal of answering the query `eat(X,jerry)` to the subgoals of first finding an X such that `big(X)` holds and then of showing that `small(jerry)` holds.
[src:altair-viz/declarative-programming] It repeatedly uses rules to further reduce subgoals to other subgoals, until it eventually succeeds in unifying all subgoals with facts in the program.
[src:altair-viz/declarative-programming] This backward reasoning, goal-reduction strategy treats rules in logic programs as procedures, and makes Prolog both a declarative and procedural programming language.
[src:altair-viz/declarative-programming] The broad range of Prolog applications is highlighted in the Year of Prolog Book, celebrating the 50 year anniversary of Prolog.
[src:altair-viz/declarative-programming] The origins of Datalog date back to the beginning of logic programming, but it was identified as a separate area around 1977.
[src:altair-viz/declarative-programming] Syntactically and semantically, it is a subset of Prolog.
[src:altair-viz/declarative-programming] But because it lacks compound terms, it is not Turing-complete.
[src:altair-viz/declarative-programming] Most Datalog systems execute programs bottom-up, using rules to reason forwards, deriving new facts from existing facts, and terminating when there are no new facts that can be derived, or when the derived facts unify with the query.
[src:altair-viz/declarative-programming] Datalog has been applied to such problems as data integration, information extraction, networking, security, cloud computing and machine learning.
[src:altair-viz/declarative-programming] Answer set programming (ASP) evolved in the late 1990s, based on the stable model (answer set) semantics of logic programming.
[src:altair-viz/declarative-programming] Like Datalog, it is a subset of Prolog; and, because it lacks compound terms, it is not Turing-complete.
[src:altair-viz/declarative-programming] Most implementations of ASP execute a program by first *grounding* the program, replacing all variables in rules by constants in all possible ways, and then using a propositional SAT solver, such as the DPLL algorithm to generate one or more models of the program.
[src:altair-viz/declarative-programming] Its applications are oriented towards solving difficult search problems and knowledge representation.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] Web browsers have a dedicated JavaScript engine that executes the client code.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] These engines are also utilized in some servers and a variety of apps.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] The most popular runtime system for non-browser usage is Node.js.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] JavaScript is a high-level, often just-in-time–compiled language that conforms to the ECMAScript standard.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] It has dynamic typing, prototype-based object-orientation, and first-class functions.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] It is multi-paradigm, supporting event-driven, functional, and imperative programming styles.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] It has application programming interfaces (APIs) for working with text, dates, regular expressions, standard data structures, and the Document Object Model (DOM).
[src:altair-viz/javascript] The ECMAScript standard does not include any input/output (I/O), such as networking, storage, or graphics facilities.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] In practice, the web browser or other runtime system provides JavaScript APIs for I/O.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] Although Java and JavaScript are similar in name and syntax, the two languages are distinct and differ greatly in design.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] The first popular web browser with a graphical user interface, Mosaic, was released in 1993.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] The lead developers of Mosaic then founded the Netscape corporation, which released a more polished browser, Netscape Navigator, in 1994.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] During these formative years of the Web, web pages could only be static, lacking the capability for dynamic behavior after the page was loaded in the browser.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] There was a desire in the flourishing web development scene to remove this limitation, so in 1995, Netscape decided to add a programming language to Navigator.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] They pursued two routes to achieve this: collaborating with Sun Microsystems to embed the Java language, while also hiring Brendan Eich to embed the Scheme language.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] The goal was a "language for the masses", "to help nonprogrammers create dynamic, interactive Web sites".
[src:altair-viz/javascript] Netscape management soon decided that the best option was for Eich to devise a new language, with syntax similar to Java and less like Scheme or other extant scripting languages.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] Although the new language and its interpreter implementation were called LiveScript when first shipped as part of a Navigator beta in September 1995, the name was changed to JavaScript for the official release in December.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] The choice of the *JavaScript* name has caused confusion, implying that it is directly related to Java.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] At the time, the dot-com boom had begun and Java was a popular new language, so Eich considered the JavaScript name a marketing ploy by Netscape.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] Microsoft debuted Internet Explorer in 1995, leading to a browser war with Netscape.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] On the JavaScript front, Microsoft created its own interpreter called JScript.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] Microsoft first released JScript in 1996, alongside initial support for CSS and extensions to HTML.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] Each of these implementations was noticeably different from their counterparts in Netscape Navigator.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] These differences made it difficult for developers to make their websites work well in both browsers, leading to widespread use of "best viewed in Netscape" and "best viewed in Internet Explorer" logos for several years.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] In November 1996, Netscape submitted JavaScript to Ecma International, as the starting point for a standard specification that all browser vendors could conform to.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] This led to the official release of the first ECMAScript language specification in June 1997.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] The standards process continued for a few years, with the release of ECMAScript 2 in June 1998 and ECMAScript 3 in December 1999.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] However, the effort to fully standardize the language was undermined by Microsoft gaining an increasingly dominant position in the browser market.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] By the early 2000s, Internet Explorer's market share reached 95%.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] This meant that JScript became the de facto standard for client-side scripting on the Web.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] Microsoft initially participated in the standards process and implemented some proposals in its JScript language, but eventually it stopped collaborating on ECMA work.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] During the period of Internet Explorer dominance in the early 2000s, client-side scripting was stagnant.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] This started to change in 2004, when the successor of Netscape, Mozilla, released the Firefox browser.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] Firefox was well received by many, taking significant market share from Internet Explorer.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] In 2005, Mozilla joined ECMA International, and work started on the ECMAScript for XML (E4X) standard.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] This led to Mozilla working jointly with Macromedia (later acquired by Adobe Systems), who were implementing E4X in their ActionScript 3 language, which was based on an ECMAScript 4 draft.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] The goal became standardizing ActionScript 3 as the new ECMAScript 4.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] To this end, Adobe Systems released the Tamarin implementation as an open source project.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] However, Tamarin and ActionScript 3 were too different from established client-side scripting, and without cooperation from Microsoft, ECMAScript 4 never reached fruition.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] Meanwhile, very important developments were occurring in open-source communities not affiliated with ECMA work.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] In 2005, Jesse James Garrett released a white paper in which he coined the term Ajax and described a set of technologies, of which JavaScript was the backbone, to create web applications where data can be loaded in the background, avoiding the need for full page reloads.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] This sparked a renaissance period of JavaScript, spearheaded by open-source libraries and the communities that formed around them.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] Many new libraries were created, including jQuery, Prototype, Dojo Toolkit, and MooTools.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] Google debuted its Chrome browser in 2008, with the V8 JavaScript engine that was faster than its competition.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] The key innovation was just-in-time compilation (JIT), so other browser vendors needed to overhaul their engines for JIT.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] In July 2008, these disparate parties came together for a conference in Oslo.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] This led to the eventual agreement in early 2009 to combine all relevant work and drive the language forward.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] The result was the ECMAScript 5 standard, released in December 2009.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] Ambitious work on the language continued for several years, culminating in an extensive collection of additions and refinements being formalized with the publication of ECMAScript 6 in 2015.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] The creation of Node.js in 2009 by Ryan Dahl sparked a significant increase in the usage of JavaScript outside of web browsers.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] Node combines the V8 engine, an event loop, and I/O APIs, thereby providing a stand-alone JavaScript runtime system.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] As of 2018, Node had been used by millions of developers, and npm had the most modules of any package manager in the world.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] The ECMAScript draft specification is currently maintained openly on GitHub, and editions are produced via regular annual snapshots.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] Potential revisions to the language are vetted through a comprehensive proposal process.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] Now, instead of edition numbers, developers check the status of upcoming features individually.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] The current JavaScript ecosystem has many libraries and frameworks, established programming practices, and substantial usage of JavaScript outside of web browsers.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] Plus, with the rise of single-page applications and other JavaScript-heavy websites, several transpilers have been created to aid the development process.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] As of 2025, the overwhelming majority of websites (98.9%) use JavaScript for client side webpage behavior.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] "JavaScript" is a trademark of Oracle Corporation in the United States.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] The trademark was originally issued to Sun Microsystems on 6 May 1997, and was transferred to Oracle when they acquired Sun in 2009.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] A letter was circulated in September 2024, spearheaded by Ryan Dahl, calling on Oracle to free the JavaScript trademark.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] Brendan Eich, the original creator of JavaScript, was among the over 14,000 signatories who supported the initiative.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] JavaScript is the dominant client-side scripting language of the Web, with 99% of all websites using it for this purpose.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] Scripts are embedded in or included from HTML documents and interact with the DOM.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] All major web browsers have a built-in JavaScript engine that executes the code on the user's device.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] Over 80% of websites use a third-party JavaScript library or web framework as part of their client-side scripting.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] Other notable ones include Angular, Bootstrap, Lodash, Modernizr, React, Underscore, and Vue.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] Multiple options can be used in conjunction, such as jQuery and Bootstrap.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] However, the term "Vanilla JS" was coined for websites not using any libraries or frameworks at all, instead relying entirely on standard JavaScript functionality.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] The use of JavaScript has expanded beyond its web browser roots.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] JavaScript engines are now embedded in a variety of other software systems, both for server-side website deployments and non-browser applications.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] Initial attempts at promoting server-side JavaScript usage were Netscape Enterprise Server and Microsoft's Internet Information Services, but they were small niches.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] Server-side usage eventually started to grow in the late 2000s, with the creation of Node.js and other approaches.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] Electron, Cordova, React Native, and other application frameworks have been used to create many applications with behavior implemented in JavaScript.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] Other non-browser applications include Adobe Acrobat support for scripting PDF documents and GNOME Shell extensions written in JavaScript.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] Oracle used to provide Nashorn, a JavaScript interpreter, as part of their Java Development Kit (JDK) API library along with **jjs** a command line interpreter as of JDK version 8.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] As a replacement Oracle offered GraalJS which can also be used with the OpenJDK which allows one to create and reference Java objects in JavaScript code and add runtime scripting in JavaScript to applications written in Java.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] JavaScript has been used in some embedded systems, usually by leveraging Node.js.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] The first JavaScript engines were interpreters of the source code, but modern engines use just-in-time compilation to improve performance.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] JavaScript engines are typically developed by web browser vendors, and every major browser includes one.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] In a browser, the JavaScript engine runs in concert with the rendering engine via the Document Object Model and Web IDL bindings.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] However, the use of JavaScript engines is not limited to browsers; For example, the V8 engine is a core component of the Node.js runtime system.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] They are also called ECMAScript engines, after the official name of the specification.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] With the advent of WebAssembly, some engines can also execute this code in the same sandbox as regular JavaScript code.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] A JavaScript engine must be embedded within a runtime system (such as a web browser or a standalone system) to enable scripts to interact with the broader environment.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] The runtime system includes the necessary APIs for input/output operations, such as networking, storage, and graphics, and provides the ability to import scripts.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] JavaScript is a single-threaded language.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] The runtime processes messages from a queue one at a time, and it calls a function associated with each new message, creating a call stack frame with the function's arguments and local variables.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] The call stack shrinks and grows based on the function's needs.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] When the call stack is empty upon function completion, JavaScript proceeds to the next message in the queue.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] This is called the event loop, described as "run to completion" because each message is fully processed before the next message is considered.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] However, the language's concurrency model describes the event loop as non-blocking: program I/O is performed using events and callback functions.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] This means, for example, that JavaScript can process a mouse click while waiting for a database query to return information.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] The notable standalone runtimes are Node.js, Deno, and Bun.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] The following features are common to all conforming ECMAScript implementations unless explicitly specified otherwise.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] The number of cited reserved words including keywords is 50–60 and varies depending on the implementation.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] JavaScript supports much of the structured programming syntax from C (e.g., `if` statements, `while` loops, `switch` statements, `do while` loops, etc.).
[src:altair-viz/javascript] One partial exception is scoping: originally JavaScript only had function scoping with `var`; block scoping was added in ECMAScript 2015 with the keywords `let` and `const`.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] Like C, JavaScript makes a distinction between expressions and statements.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] One syntactic difference from C is automatic semicolon insertion, which allow semicolons (which terminate statements) to be omitted.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] JavaScript is weakly typed, which means certain types are implicitly cast depending on the operation used.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] Values are cast to numbers by casting to strings and then casting the strings to numbers.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] These processes can be modified by defining `toString` and `valueOf` functions on the prototype for string and number casting respectively.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] JavaScript has received criticism for the way it implements these conversions as the complexity of the rules can be mistaken for inconsistency.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] For example, when adding a number to a string, the number will be cast to a string before performing concatenation, but when subtracting a number from a string, the string is cast to a number before performing subtraction.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] Often also mentioned is `{} + []` resulting in `0` (number).
[src:altair-viz/javascript] This is misleading: the `{}` is interpreted as an empty code block instead of an empty object, and the empty array is cast to a number by the remaining unary `+` operator.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] If the expression is wrapped in parentheses - `({} + [])` – the curly brackets are interpreted as an empty object and the result of the expression is `"[object Object]"` as expected.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] JavaScript is dynamically typed like most other scripting languages.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] A type is associated with a value rather than an expression.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] For example, a variable initially bound to a number may be reassigned to a string.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] JavaScript supports various ways to test the type of objects, including duck typing.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] JavaScript includes an `eval` function that can execute statements provided as strings at run-time.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] In JavaScript, an object is an associative array, augmented with a prototype (see below); each key provides the name for an object property, and there are two syntactical ways to specify such a name: dot notation (`obj.x = 10`) and bracket notation (`obj["x"] = 10`).
[src:altair-viz/javascript] A property may be added, rebound, or deleted at run-time.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] Most properties of an object (and any property that belongs to an object's prototype inheritance chain) can be enumerated using a `for...in` loop.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] JavaScript uses prototypes where many other object-oriented languages use classes for inheritance, but it's still possible to simulate most class-based features with the prototype system.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] Additionally, ECMAScript version 6 (released June 2015) introduced the keywords **class**, **extends** and **super**, which serve as syntactic sugar to abstract the underlying prototypal inheritance system with a more conventional interface.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] Constructors are declared by specifying a method named **constructor**, and all classes are automatically subclasses of the base class Object, similarly to Java.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] Though the underlying object mechanism is still based on prototypes, the newer syntax is similar to other object oriented languages.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] Private variables are declared by prefixing the field name with a number sign (#), and polymorphism is not directly supported, although it can be emulated by manually calling different functions depending on the number and type of arguments provided.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] Functions double as object constructors, along with their typical role.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] Prefixing a function call with *new* will create an instance of a prototype, inheriting properties and methods from the constructor (including properties from the `Object` prototype).
[src:altair-viz/javascript] ECMAScript 5 offers the `Object.create` method, allowing explicit creation of an instance without automatically inheriting from the `Object` prototype (older environments can assign the prototype to `null`).
[src:altair-viz/javascript] The constructor's `prototype` property determines the object used for the new object's internal prototype.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] New methods can be added by modifying the prototype of the function used as a constructor.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] JavaScript's built-in classes, such as `Array` and `Object`, also have prototypes that can be modified.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] However, it's generally considered bad practice to modify built-in objects, because third-party code may use or inherit methods and properties from these objects, and may not expect the prototype to be modified.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] Unlike in many object-oriented languages, in JavaScript there is no distinction between a function definition and a method definition.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] Rather, the distinction occurs during function calling.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] When a function is called as a method of an object, the function's local *this* keyword is bound to that object for that invocation.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] JavaScript functions are first-class; a function is considered to be an object.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] As such, a function may have properties and methods, such as `.call()` and `.bind()`.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] A *nested* function is a function defined within another function.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] It is created each time the outer function is invoked.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] In addition, each nested function forms a lexical closure: the lexical scope of the outer function (including any constant, local variable, or argument value) becomes part of the internal state of each inner function object, even after execution of the outer function concludes.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] JavaScript also supports anonymous functions.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] JavaScript supports implicit and explicit delegation.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] JavaScript natively supports various function-based implementations of Role patterns like Traits and Mixins.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] Such a function defines additional behavior by at least one method bound to the `this` keyword within its `function` body.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] A Role then has to be delegated explicitly via `call` or `apply` to objects that need to feature additional behavior that is not shared via the prototype chain.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] Whereas explicit function-based delegation does cover composition in JavaScript, implicit delegation already happens every time the prototype chain is walked in order to, e.g., find a method that might be related to but is not directly owned by an object.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] Once the method is found it gets called within this object's context.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] Thus inheritance in JavaScript is covered by a delegation automatism that is bound to the prototype property of constructor functions.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] An indefinite number of parameters can be passed to a function.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] The function can access them through formal parameters and also through the local `arguments` object.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] Variadic functions can also be created by using the `bind` method.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] Like in many scripting languages, arrays and objects (associative arrays in other languages) can each be created with a succinct shortcut syntax.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] In fact, these literals form the basis of the JSON data format.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] JavaScript supports regular expressions for text searches and manipulation.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] A built-in Promise object provides functionality for handling promises and associating handlers with an asynchronous action's eventual result.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] JavaScript supplies combinator methods, which allow developers to combine multiple JavaScript promises and do operations based on different scenarios.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] The methods introduced are: Promise.race, Promise.all, Promise.allSettled and Promise.any.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] Async/await allows an asynchronous, non-blocking function to be structured in a way similar to an ordinary synchronous function.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] Asynchronous, non-blocking code can be written, with minimal overhead, structured similarly to traditional synchronous, blocking code.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] Variables in JavaScript can be defined using either the `var`, `let` or `const` keywords.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] Variables defined without keywords will be defined at the global scope.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] Arrow functions were first introduced in 6th Edition – ECMAScript 2015.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] They shorten the syntax for writing functions in JavaScript.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] Arrow functions are anonymous, so a variable is needed to refer to them in order to invoke them after their creation, unless surrounded by parenthesis and executed immediately.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] Here is an example of JavaScript syntax.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] Note the comments in the examples above, all of which were preceded with two forward slashes.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] More examples can be found at the Wikibooks page on JavaScript syntax examples.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] JavaScript and the DOM provide the potential for malicious authors to deliver scripts to run on a client computer via the Web.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] Browser authors minimize this risk using two restrictions.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] First, scripts run in a sandbox in which they can only perform Web-related actions, not general-purpose programming tasks like creating files.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] Second, scripts are constrained by the same-origin policy: scripts from one website do not have access to information such as usernames, passwords, or cookies sent to another site.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] Most JavaScript-related security bugs are breaches of either the same origin policy or the sandbox.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] There are subsets of general JavaScript—ADsafe, Secure ECMAScript (SES)—that provide greater levels of security, especially on code created by third parties (such as advertisements).
[src:altair-viz/javascript] Closure Toolkit is another project for safe embedding and isolation of third-party JavaScript and HTML.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] Content Security Policy is the main intended method of ensuring that only trusted code is executed on a Web page.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] A common JavaScript-related security problem is cross-site scripting (XSS), a violation of the same-origin policy.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] XSS vulnerabilities occur when an attacker can cause a target Website, such as an online banking website, to include a malicious script in the webpage presented to a victim.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] The script in this example can then access the banking application with the privileges of the victim, potentially disclosing secret information or transferring money without the victim's authorization.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] One important solution to XSS vulnerabilities is HTML sanitization.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] Some browsers include partial protection against *reflected* XSS attacks, in which the attacker provides a URL including malicious script.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] However, even users of those browsers are vulnerable to other XSS attacks, such as those where the malicious code is stored in a database.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] Only correct design of Web applications on the server-side can fully prevent XSS.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] XSS vulnerabilities can also occur because of implementation mistakes by browser authors.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] Another cross-site vulnerability is cross-site request forgery (CSRF).
[src:altair-viz/javascript] In CSRF, code on an attacker's site tricks the victim's browser into taking actions the user did not intend at a target site (like transferring money at a bank).
[src:altair-viz/javascript] When target sites rely solely on cookies for request authentication, requests originating from code on the attacker's site can carry the same valid login credentials of the initiating user.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] In general, the solution to CSRF is to require an authentication value in a hidden form field, and not only in the cookies, to authenticate any request that might have lasting effects.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] Checking the HTTP Referrer header can also help.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] "JavaScript hijacking" is a type of CSRF attack in which a `<script>` tag on an attacker's site exploits a page on the victim's site that returns private information such as JSON or JavaScript.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] Developers of client-server applications must recognize that untrusted clients may be under the control of attackers.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] The author of an application should not assume that their JavaScript code will run as intended (or at all) because any secret embedded in the code could be extracted by a determined adversary.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] Package management systems such as npm and Bower are popular with JavaScript developers.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] Such systems allow a developer to easily manage their program's dependencies upon other developers' program libraries.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] Developers trust that the maintainers of the libraries will keep them secure and up to date, but that is not always the case.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] A vulnerability has emerged because of this blind trust.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] Relied-upon libraries can have new releases that cause bugs or vulnerabilities to appear in all programs that rely upon the libraries.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] Inversely, a library can go unpatched with known vulnerabilities out in the wild.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] In a study done looking over a sample of 133,000 websites, researchers found 37% of the websites included a library with at least one known vulnerability.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] This occurred in March 2016 when Azer Koçulu removed his repository from npm.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] This caused tens of thousands of programs and websites depending upon his libraries to break.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] JavaScript provides an interface to a wide range of browser capabilities, some of which may have flaws such as buffer overflows.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] These flaws can allow attackers to write scripts that would run any code they wish on the user's system.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] This code is not by any means limited to another JavaScript application.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] For example, a buffer overrun exploit can allow an attacker to gain access to the operating system's API with superuser privileges.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] These flaws have affected major browsers including Firefox, Internet Explorer, and Safari.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] Plugins, such as video players, Adobe Flash, and the wide range of ActiveX controls enabled by default in Microsoft Internet Explorer, may also have flaws exploitable via JavaScript (such flaws have been exploited in the past).
[src:altair-viz/javascript] In Windows Vista, Microsoft has attempted to contain the risks of bugs such as buffer overflows by running the Internet Explorer process with limited privileges.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] Google Chrome similarly confines its page renderers to their own "sandbox".
[src:altair-viz/javascript] Web browsers are capable of running JavaScript outside the sandbox, with the privileges necessary to, for example, create or delete files.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] Such privileges are not intended to be granted to code from the Web.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] Incorrectly granting privileges to JavaScript from the Web has played a role in vulnerabilities in both Internet Explorer and Firefox.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] In Windows XP Service Pack 2, Microsoft demoted JScript's privileges in Internet Explorer.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] Microsoft Windows allows JavaScript source files on a computer's hard drive to be launched as general-purpose, non-sandboxed programs (see: Windows Script Host).
[src:altair-viz/javascript] This makes JavaScript (like VBScript) a theoretically viable vector for a Trojan horse, although JavaScript Trojan horses are uncommon in practice.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] In 2015, a JavaScript-based proof-of-concept implementation of a rowhammer attack was described in a paper by security researchers.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] In 2017, a JavaScript-based attack via browser was demonstrated that could bypass ASLR.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] In 2018, the paper that announced the Spectre attacks against Speculative Execution in Intel and other processors included a JavaScript implementation.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] Important tools have evolved with the language.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] A common misconception is that JavaScript is directly related to Java.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] Both indeed have a C-like syntax (the C language being their most immediate common ancestor language).
[src:altair-viz/javascript] They are also typically sandboxed, and JavaScript was designed with Java's syntax and standard library in mind.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] In particular, all Java keywords were reserved in original JavaScript, JavaScript's standard library follows Java's naming conventions, and JavaScript's `Math` and `Date` objects are based on classes from Java 1.0.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] Both languages first appeared in 1995, but Java was developed by James Gosling of Sun Microsystems and JavaScript by Brendan Eich of Netscape Communications.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] The differences between the two languages are more prominent than their similarities.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] Java has static typing, while JavaScript's typing is dynamic.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] Java is loaded from compiled bytecode, while JavaScript is loaded as human-readable source code.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] Java's objects are class-based, while JavaScript's are prototype-based.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] Finally, Java did not support functional programming until Java 8, while JavaScript has done so from the beginning, being influenced by Scheme.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] JSON is a data format derived from JavaScript; hence the name JavaScript Object Notation.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] It is a widely used format supported by many other programming languages.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] Many websites are JavaScript-heavy, so transpilers have been created to convert code written in other languages, which can aid the development process.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] TypeScript and CoffeeScript are two notable languages that transpile to JavaScript.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] WebAssembly is a newer language with a bytecode format designed to complement JavaScript, especially the performance-critical portions of web page scripts.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] All of the major JavaScript engines support WebAssembly, which runs in the same sandbox as regular JavaScript code.
[src:altair-viz/javascript] asm.js is a subset of JavaScript that served as the forerunner of WebAssembly.
[src:altair-viz/overview] Vega-Altair is a declarative statistical visualization library for Python, based on Vega and Vega-Lite.
[src:altair-viz/overview] It offers a powerful and concise grammar that enables you to quickly build a wide range of statistical visualizations.
[src:altair-viz/overview] The key idea is that you are declaring links between *data columns* and *visual encoding channels*, such as the x-axis, y-axis and color.
[src:altair-viz/overview] The rest of the plot details are handled automatically.
[src:altair-viz/overview] Building on this declarative system, a surprising range of plots, from simple to sophisticated, can be created using a concise grammar.
[src:altair-viz/overview] The project is named after the brightest star in the constellation Aquila.
[src:altair-viz/overview] From Earth’s sky Altair appears close to Vega, the star from which our parent project drew its name.
[src:altair-viz/overview] This documentation serves as the main reference for learning about Altair.
[src:altair-viz/overview] Additional learning material and tutorials can be found in the Learning Material section.
[src:altair-viz/overview] It can also be helpful to browse the Vega-Lite documentation.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] SVG images are defined in a vector graphics format and stored in XML text files.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] SVG images can thus be scaled in size without loss of quality, and SVG files can be searched, indexed, scripted, and compressed.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] The XML text files can be created and edited with text editors or vector graphics editors, and are rendered by most web browsers.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] SVG can include JavaScript, potentially leading to cross-site scripting.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] SVG has been in development within the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C) since 1999 after six competing proposals for vector graphics languages had been submitted to the consortium during 1998 (see below).
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] The early SVG Working Group decided not to develop any of the commercial submissions, but to create a new markup language that was informed by but not really based on any of them.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] The working group was chaired at the time by Chris Lilley of the W3C.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] Early adoption was limited due to lack of support in older versions of Internet Explorer.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] However, as of 2011, all major desktop browsers began to support SVG.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] Native browser support offers various advantages, such as not requiring plugins, allowing SVG to be mixed with other content, and improving rendering and scripting reliability.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] Mobile support for SVG exists in various forms, with different devices and browsers supporting SVG Tiny 1.1 or 1.2.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] SVG can be produced using vector graphics editors and rendered into raster formats.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] In web-based applications, Inline SVG allows embedding SVG content within HTML documents.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] The SVG specification was updated to version 1.1 in 2011.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] Scalable Vector Graphics 2 became a W3C Candidate Recommendation on 15 September 2016.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] SVG 2 incorporates several new features in addition to those of SVG 1.1 and SVG Tiny 1.2.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] SVG 2 reached the Candidate Recommendation stage on 15 September 2016, and revised versions were published on 7 August 2018 and 4 October 2018.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] The latest draft was released on 14 September 2025.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] SVG supports interactivity, animation, and rich graphical capabilities, making it suitable for both web and print applications.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] SVG images can be compressed with the gzip algorithm, resulting in SVGZ files that are typically 20–50% smaller than the original.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] SVG also supports metadata, enabling better indexing, searching, and retrieval of SVG content.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] SVG allows three types of graphic objects: vector graphic shapes (such as paths consisting of straight lines and curves), bitmap images, and text.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] Graphical objects can be grouped, styled, transformed and composited into previously rendered objects.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] The feature set includes nested transformations, clipping paths, alpha masks, filter effects and template objects.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] SVG drawings can be interactive and can include animation, defined in the SVG XML elements or via scripting that accesses the SVG Document Object Model (DOM).
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] SVG uses CSS for styling and JavaScript for scripting.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] Text, including internationalization and localization, appearing in plain text within the SVG DOM, enhances the accessibility of SVG graphics.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] Though the SVG Specification primarily focuses on vector graphics markup language, its design includes the basic capabilities of a page description language like Adobe's PDF.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] It contains provisions for rich graphics, and is compatible with CSS for styling purposes.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] SVG has the information needed to place each glyph and image in a chosen location on a printed page.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] SVG drawings can be dynamic and interactive.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] Time-based modifications to the elements can be described in SMIL, or can be programmed in a scripting language (e.g.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] The W3C explicitly recommends SMIL as the standard for animation in SVG.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] A rich set of event handlers such as "onmouseover" and "onclick" can be assigned to any SVG graphical object to apply actions and events.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] Because of industry demand, two mobile profiles were introduced with SVG 1.1: *SVG Tiny* (SVGT) and *SVG Basic* (SVGB).
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] These are subsets of the full SVG standard, mainly intended for user agents with limited capabilities.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] In particular, SVG Tiny was defined for highly restricted mobile devices such as cellphones; it does not support styling or scripting.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] SVG Basic was defined for higher-level mobile devices, such as smartphones.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] In 2003, the 3GPP, an international telecommunications standards group, adopted SVG Tiny as the mandatory vector graphics media format for next-generation phones.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] SVGT is the required vector graphics format and support of SVGB is optional for Multimedia Messaging Service (MMS) and Packet-switched Streaming Service.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] It was later added as required format for vector graphics in 3GPP IP Multimedia Subsystem (IMS).
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] Neither mobile profile includes support for the full Document Object Model (DOM), while only SVG Basic has optional support for scripting, but because they are fully compatible subsets of the full standard, most SVG graphics can still be rendered by devices which only support the mobile profiles.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] SVGT 1.2 adds a microDOM (μDOM), styling and scripting.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] SVGT 1.2 also includes some features not found in SVG 1.1, including non-scaling strokes, which are supported by some SVG 1.1 implementations, such as Opera, Firefox, and WebKit.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] As shared code bases between desktop and mobile browsers increased, the use of SVG 1.1 over SVGT 1.2 also increased.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] SVG images, being XML, contain many repeated fragments of text, so they are well suited for lossless data compression algorithms.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] When an SVG image has been compressed with the gzip algorithm, it is referred to as an "SVGZ" image and uses the corresponding `.svgz` filename extension.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] Conforming SVG 1.1 viewers will display compressed images.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] An SVGZ file is typically 20 to 50 percent of the original size.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] W3C provides SVGZ files to test for conformance.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] (for "line to") precedes a point to which a line should be drawn.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] In all cases, absolute coordinates follow capital letter commands and relative coordinates are used after the equivalent lower-case letters.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] Straight-line paths and paths made up of a series of connected straight-line segments (polylines), as well as closed polygons, circles, and ellipses can be drawn.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] Rectangles and round-cornered rectangles are also standard elements.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] SVG shapes can be filled and outlined (painted with a color, a gradient, or a pattern).
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] Fills may be opaque, or have any degree of transparency.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] "Markers" are line-end features, such as arrowheads, or symbols that can appear at the vertices of a polygon.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] SVG shapes can be filled or outlined with solid colors as above, or with color gradients or with repeating patterns.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] Color gradients can be linear or radial (circular), and can involve any number of colors as well as repeats.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] Opacity gradients can also be specified.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] Gradients and patterns can be animated and scripted.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] could usefully be added to the SVG specification.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] The current draft of SVG 2 includes gradient meshes.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] regions that can be painted (with colors, gradients and patterns) independently.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] SVG images can interact with users in many ways.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] , mouse clicks, scrolling or zooming the image and other pointer, keyboard and document events.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] Event handlers may start, stop or alter animations as well as trigger scripts in response to such events.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] can link to SVG files that change the visible area of the document.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] This allows for creating specific view states that are used to zoom in/out of a specific area or to limit the view to a specific element.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] element also allow linking to and re-using internal and external elements.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] This allows coders to do more with less markup and makes for cleaner code.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] All aspects of an SVG document can be accessed and manipulated using scripts in a similar way to HTML.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] (DOM) objects for every SVG element and attribute.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] They can run in response to pointer events, keyboard events and document events as required.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] Content can be animated by manipulating the DOM using ECMAScript and the scripting language's built-in timers.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] Animations can be continuous, they can loop and repeat, and they can respond to user events, as mentioned above.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] As with HTML and CSS, text in SVG may reference external font files, such as system fonts.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] If the required font files do not exist on the machine where the SVG file is rendered, the text may not appear as intended.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] metadata properties (e.g. title, creator/author, subject, description, etc.).
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] Other metadata schemas may also be used.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] elements where authors may also provide plain-text descriptive material within an SVG image to help indexing, searching and retrieval by a number of means.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] An SVG document can define components including shapes, gradients etc., and use them repeatedly.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] SVG images can also contain raster graphics, such as PNG and JPEG images, and further SVG images.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] The use of SVG on the web was limited by the lack of support in older versions of Internet Explorer (IE).
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] Many websites that serve SVG images also provide the images in a raster format, either automatically by HTTP content negotiation or by allowing the user directly to choose the file.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] Konqueror was the first browser to support SVG in release version 3.2 in February 2004.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] As of 2011, all major desktop browsers, and many minor ones, have some level of SVG support.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] Other browsers' implementations are not yet complete; see comparison of layout engines for further details.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] However, SVG images may be included in XHTML pages using XML namespaces.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] Tim Berners-Lee, the inventor of the World Wide Web, was critical of early versions of Internet Explorer for its failure to support SVG.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] There are several advantages to native and full support: plugins are not needed, SVG can be freely mixed with other content in a single document, and rendering and scripting become considerably more reliable.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] Support for SVG may be limited to SVGT on older or more limited smart phones or may be primarily limited by their respective operating system.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] Adobe Flash Lite has optionally supported SVG Tiny since version 1.1.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] At the SVG Open 2005 conference, Sun demonstrated a mobile implementation of SVG Tiny 1.1 for the Connected Limited Device Configuration (CLDC) platform.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] Mobiles that use Opera Mobile, as well as the iPhone's built in browser, also include SVG support.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] However, even though it used the WebKit engine, the Android built-in browser did not support SVG prior to v3.0 (Honeycomb).
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] Prior to v3.0, Firefox Mobile 4.0b2 (beta) for Android was the first browser running under Android to support SVG by default.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] The level of SVG Tiny support available varies from mobile to mobile, depending on the SVG engine installed.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] Many newer mobile products support additional features beyond SVG Tiny 1.1, like gradient and opacity; this is sometimes referred to as "SVGT 1.1+", though there is no such standard.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] RIM's BlackBerry has built-in support for SVG Tiny 1.1 since version 5.0.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] Support continues for WebKit-based BlackBerry Torch browser in OS 6 and 7.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] Nokia's S60 platform has built-in support for SVG.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] For example, icons are generally rendered using the platform's SVG engine.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] Nokia has also led the JSR 226: Scalable 2D Vector Graphics API expert group that defines Java ME API for SVG presentation and manipulation.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] This API has been implemented in S60 Platform 3rd Edition Feature Pack 1 and onward.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] Some Series 40 phones also support SVG (such as Nokia 6280).
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] Most Sony Ericsson phones beginning with K700 (by release date) support SVG Tiny 1.1.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] Phones beginning with K750 also support such features as opacity and gradients.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] Phones with Sony Ericsson Java Platform-8 have support for JSR 226.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] Windows Phone has supported SVG since version 7.5.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] SVG is also supported on various mobile devices from Motorola, Samsung, LG, and Siemens mobile/BenQ-Siemens. eSVG, an SVG rendering library mainly written for embedded devices, is available on some mobile platforms.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] SVG images can be hand-coded or produced by the use of a vector graphics editor, such as Inkscape, Adobe Illustrator, Adobe Animate, or CorelDRAW, and rendered to common raster image formats such as PNG using the same software.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] Additionally, editors like Inkscape and Boxy SVG provide tools to trace raster images to Bézier curves typically using image tracing back-ends like potrace, autotrace, and imagetracerjs.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] Software can be programmed to render SVG images by using a library such as librsvg used by GNOME since 2000, Batik and ThorVG since 2020 for lightweight systems.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] SVG images can also be rendered to any desired popular image format by using ImageMagick, a free command-line utility (which also uses librsvg under the hood).
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] For web-based applications, the mode of usage termed Inline SVG allows SVG content to be embedded within an HTML document using an `<svg>` tag.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] Its graphical capabilities can then be employed to create sophisticated user interfaces as the SVG and HTML share context, event handling, and CSS.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] Other uses for SVG include embedding for use in word processing (e.g. with LibreOffice) and desktop publishing (e.g.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] Scribus), plotting graphs (e.g. gnuplot), and importing paths (e.g. for use in GIMP or Blender).
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] The application services Microsoft 365 and Microsoft Office 2019 offer support for exporting, importing and editing SVG images.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] The Uniform Type Identifier for SVG used by Apple is `public.svg-image` and conforms to `public.image` and `public.xml`.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] As a document format, similar to HTML documents, SVG can host scripts or CSS.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] This is an issue when an attacker can upload a SVG file, such as a profile picture, to a website and the file is treated as a normal picture, but contains malicious content.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] For instance, if an SVG file is deployed as a CSS background image, or a logo on some website, or in some image gallery, then, when the image is loaded in a browser, it activates a script or other content.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] This could lock up the browser (the Billion laughs attack), but could also lead to HTML injection and cross-site scripting attacks.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] The W3C therefore stipulates certain requirements when SVG is simply used for images: SVG Security.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] The W3C says that Inline SVG (an SVG file loaded natively on a website) is considered less of a security risk because the content is part of a greater document, and so scripting and CSS would not be unexpected.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] The MPEG-4 Part 20 standard – *Lightweight Application Scene Representation (LASeR) and Simple Aggregation Format (SAF)* is based on SVG Tiny.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] It was developed by MPEG (ISO/IEC JTC 1/SC29/WG11) and published as ISO/IEC 14496-20:2006.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] SVG capabilities are enhanced in MPEG-4 Part 20 with key features for mobile services, such as dynamic updates, binary encoding, state-of-art font representation.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] SVG was also accommodated in MPEG-4 Part 11, in the Extensible MPEG-4 Textual (XMT) format – a textual representation of the MPEG-4 multimedia content using XML.
[src:altair-viz/scalable-vector-graphics] While SVG has received widespread adoption in the market as the de-facto standard for scalable vector graphics, the files are still not natively supported in Windows, so users must download an SVG preview thumbnailer for the File Explorer or use an alternate file explorer with native support.
[src:altair-viz/statistical-graphics] Whereas statistics and data analysis procedures generally yield their output in numeric or tabular form, graphical techniques allow such results to be displayed in some sort of pictorial form.
[src:altair-viz/statistical-graphics] They include plots such as scatter plots, histograms, probability plots, spaghetti plots, residual plots, box plots, block plots and biplots.
[src:altair-viz/statistical-graphics] Exploratory data analysis (EDA) relies heavily on such techniques.
[src:altair-viz/statistical-graphics] They can also provide insight into a data set to help with testing assumptions, model selection and regression model validation, estimator selection, relationship identification, factor effect determination, and outlier detection.
[src:altair-viz/statistical-graphics] In addition, the choice of appropriate statistical graphics can provide a convincing means of communicating the underlying message that is present in the data to others.
[src:altair-viz/statistical-graphics] If one is not using statistical graphics, then one is forfeiting insight into one or more aspects of the underlying structure of the data.
[src:altair-viz/statistical-graphics] Statistical graphics have been central to the development of science and date to the earliest attempts to analyse data.
[src:altair-viz/statistical-graphics] Many familiar forms, including bivariate plots, statistical maps, bar charts, and coordinate paper were used in the 18th century.
[src:altair-viz/statistical-graphics] Since the 1970s statistical graphics have been re-emerging as an important analytic tool with the revitalisation of computer graphics and related technologies.
[src:altair-viz/statistical-graphics] See the plots page for many more examples of statistical graphics.
